fields.descriptive_line: John Flaxman (1755-1826), sketchbook containing drawings made in Italy, c.1790.
fields.physical_description: 170 pages.  Cream ladi paper of Italian manufacture, about 1740.  bound in stiff paper with vellum spine (back cover missing).  Lettered in in ink on the front cover "-n Flaxm-".
fields.dimensions: Height: 10.5 in Volume size, Width: 8.25 in Volume size
fields.title: Sketchbook containing drawings made in Italy
fields.materials_techniques: laid paper with pencil, pen and ink and wash drawings
fields.bibliography: Victoria and Albert Museum, Department of Engraving, Illustration and Design and Department of Paintings, Accessions 1937, London: Board of Education, 1938. The full text of the record is as follows: 'FLAXMAN, John, R.A. (1755-1826). Sketchbook containing drawings made in Italy, c.1787-1794: life studies and copies of Hellenistic statues in Rome, Florence and Naples, made when the artist was commissioned to illustrate Homer, Dante and Aeschylus, and to exectue a monument to Lord Mansfield in Westminster Abbey. Pages 164-170 inscribed with notes headed "Character, Proportions and Anatomy of the Human Figure of the Greeks." 170pp. cream laid paper of Italian manufacture, c.1740 bound in stiff paper with vellum spine (back cover missing). Lettered in ink on front cover - - - n Flaxm - - - . Pencil, pen and ink and wash. E.442-1937'
